WEBVTT

00:00:00.988 --> 00:00:01.976
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.976 --> 00:00:03.952
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.952 --> 00:00:11.533
[CLICKING]

00:00:11.533 --> 00:00:12.950
SCOTT HUGHES: All
right, so we are

00:00:12.950 --> 00:00:15.590
ready to move to
the next lecture.

00:00:15.590 --> 00:00:17.010
I'm going to record today.

00:00:17.010 --> 00:00:19.100
So if we just quickly
recap the highlights

00:00:19.100 --> 00:00:21.890
of what we did in
our previous lecture,

00:00:21.890 --> 00:00:24.170
the goal of this lecture
was to take all the tools

00:00:24.170 --> 00:00:27.867
that we have built and
develop a theory of gravity.

00:00:27.867 --> 00:00:29.450
So the two ingredients
to this-- first

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:32.299
we're going to assert that we
take a valid law of physics,

00:00:32.299 --> 00:00:35.290
something that is
well-understood in a local

00:00:35.290 --> 00:00:39.010
Lorentz frames, which
we take corresponding

00:00:39.010 --> 00:00:41.840
to a freely falling frame
when gravity is invoked,

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:43.880
and we will carry it
over into a general form

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:46.850
by rewriting that law
in a tensorial form.

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:48.590
The example I went
through was that if I

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:51.980
assert that an object
is unaccelerated, then

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:53.570
I can normally
write that by saying

00:00:53.570 --> 00:00:57.800
that the proper derivative
of the velocity is zero--

00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:59.660
or if you like the
second derivative,

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:01.550
positional on the
world line is zero--

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:08.093
that carries over to saying that
the parallel transport of the

00:01:08.093 --> 00:01:10.010
of the four velocity,
along the four velocity,

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:11.180
is equal to zero.

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:14.870
If I require conservation,
local conservation of energy

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:17.390
and momentum to be asserted
in my local Lorentz

00:01:17.390 --> 00:01:19.490
frame, my freely falling
frame in the form

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:22.003
that it has zero divergence
with a partial derivative,

00:01:22.003 --> 00:01:23.420
that [? carries ?]
over in general

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:29.420
to zero derivative with
a covariant derivative.

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:31.880
Our second ingredient
is to try to understand

00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:36.090
how it is that I can build my
theory of spacetime-- excuse

00:01:36.090 --> 00:01:36.590
me.

00:01:36.590 --> 00:01:41.670
How I can build my spacetime
given a distribution of energy,

00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:44.120
matter, and momentum.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:46.940
We are guided by the Newtonian
field equation, which tells me

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.830
the Laplace operator
on Newtonian

00:01:48.830 --> 00:01:52.130
gravitational potential
is 4 pi G rho.

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:56.510
By studying the equation of
motion for Newtonian gravity

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:00.800
and comparing it to the geodesic
equation in the slow motion

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.140
limit for a spacetime
that deviates just

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:05.960
slightly from the flat space
on a special relativity,

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:09.259
we noted that this phi is
closely related to G00.

00:02:09.259 --> 00:02:12.560
It's precisely equal
to up to a factor of 2.

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:14.960
It's a bit of an offset
from the negative 1

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:18.950
that you get in the
special relativity limit.

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:21.380
We noted that this is
not a healthy equation

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:22.930
from the standpoint
of being a ten--

00:02:22.930 --> 00:02:26.150
of formulating things
in terms of tensors,

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:29.240
because rho is a particular
component of the stress energy

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.410
tensor.

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:33.320
Doesn't make any sense to
have a properly covariant eq--

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.040
if we want a properly
covariant equation,

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:38.390
it makes no sense to pick out
one component of a tensor.

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:41.750
So we upgraded rho to T mu nu.

00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:45.080
And we looked for, noting
that two derivatives

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:47.320
of the potential is something
like two derivatives

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:50.480
of the metric, which must be
two derivatives of a curvature,

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:52.850
we said, OK, it's got
to be a curvature tensor

00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:56.150
on the left-hand side, and
it's got to be a two index one,

00:02:56.150 --> 00:02:58.370
and it's got to be one
that has no divergence

00:02:58.370 --> 00:03:02.780
so that this equation respects
the local conservation

00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:04.760
of energy and momentum.

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:08.710
And that led us
by requiring that,

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:10.970
in the appropriate
limit of slow motion--

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:12.470
well, in this case,
really it's just

00:03:12.470 --> 00:03:15.020
sort of a weak deviation
from special relativity.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:18.380
By requiring this
correspondence to hold,

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:23.522
that force, the proportionality
between my curvature tensor

00:03:23.522 --> 00:03:24.980
and my stress energy
tensor will be

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:28.250
8 pi G. If you want to work in
units where the speed of light

00:03:28.250 --> 00:03:33.360
is not set equal to unity,
it's 8 pi G over C to the 4th.

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:34.860
So that's fine.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.230
This is, in fact, exactly
how Einstein originally

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:39.120
derived this.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:42.230
And it's a very physical, very--

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:45.270
it's a very physicist
kind of an argument.

00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:47.880
There is a another route
to the field equations,

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.400
though, which I would
like to talk about

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:51.480
in this next lecture.

00:04:02.590 --> 00:04:05.680
And what's interesting is
that, historically, this route

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.800
was actually developed at
almost the exact same time

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:12.340
that Einstein developed this
way of coming up with the field

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:15.850
equations that are going to
describe relativistic gravity.

00:04:15.850 --> 00:04:18.620
This particular
route helps us to--

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:21.850
I'd say it clarifies
some of the choices that

00:04:21.850 --> 00:04:24.490
are made that lead to
this particular framework

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:26.230
for the field equations.

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:28.990
And as we'll see as we get
to the end of this lecture,

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:30.910
it helps to illustrate
how it might

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:35.470
be-- if general relativity is
incomplete in some way, how

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:37.888
we might systematically
add a little bit

00:04:37.888 --> 00:04:39.430
of additional
framework, a little bit

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:41.440
of an additional structure.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:44.530
It gives us, what is
the most natural way

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:47.350
to introduce additional
degrees of freedom,

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.150
additional ways of
modifying things?

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:51.250
So the framework I'm
going to talk about today

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:55.270
is something that allows us
to much more naturally move

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:58.840
beyond what this might
be, just in case--

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.120
Einstein, at some
point, we're going

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:03.490
to likely find that
general relativity is not

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:04.270
quite adequate.

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:06.340
It doesn't describe
everything to the degree

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.800
that we are able to
measure everything.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:13.500
This will give us the
tools to go beyond that.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:16.120
So the particular route
I'm going to [? derive ?]

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:21.700
is found by varying a
particular Lagrangian.

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:23.080
We're going to
essentially define

00:05:23.080 --> 00:05:27.086
an action principle for the
gravitational interaction.

00:05:27.086 --> 00:05:31.450
So I will call this
lecture the field equation

00:05:31.450 --> 00:05:40.136
via the Einstein-Hilbert action.

00:05:43.970 --> 00:05:46.850
That is the same Hilbert of
Hilbert Spaces, David Hilbert,

00:05:46.850 --> 00:05:50.840
mathematician who was active
at about the same time

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:56.840
that Einstein was at his
peak research productivity.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:05:59.600
As I said, this way of
thinking about things

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:03.500
and this formulation that
allows us to re-derive this,

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:05.660
it was developed
almost in parallel

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:09.260
to Einstein's formulation
of general relativity,

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:12.440
so much so that they
practically overlapped.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:15.140
But it must be said that
Hilbert gives priority

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:16.130
to Einstein on this.

00:06:16.130 --> 00:06:17.760
Hilbert gave
Einstein the priority

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:21.350
because he felt that Einstein
really clarified the physics.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:24.860
And it was his insights that
led to this way of thinking

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:27.177
about gravity, even
though in some ways

00:06:27.177 --> 00:06:28.760
he came up with a
way of understanding

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:31.430
where the field equations come
from that is somewhat more

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:32.330
elegant.

00:06:32.330 --> 00:06:34.445
So let me first
sketch schematically

00:06:34.445 --> 00:06:35.570
how we're going to do this.

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:50.470
Schematically, what we
do is we define an action

00:06:50.470 --> 00:07:03.645
as the integral of a Lagrange
density over all of spacetime.

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:15.560
So we're going to
write our action as S,

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:19.880
and we're going to write it as
an integral over our spacetime

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:26.560
coordinates of some
Lagrange density.

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:28.630
So this is not a lot
in field theories.

00:07:28.630 --> 00:07:30.370
This Lagrange
density is something

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:35.290
that depends on the
fields you are studying.

00:07:43.090 --> 00:07:45.820
The action must itself
be a Lorentz scalar.

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:47.530
If I'm working in a
freely falling frame,

00:07:47.530 --> 00:07:51.280
it cannot be something that
depends upon the particular

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:52.990
frame that one is using.

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:54.955
And so one often writes this.

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:00.850
You explicitly call
out the square root

00:08:00.850 --> 00:08:04.120
of minus G. That is
necessary in order

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:06.580
to make your little
coordinate interval here

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:09.950
be a proper volume integral.

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:12.760
And just to make a little bit
of a notational difference,

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:16.930
let's call L hat the version
of the Lagrange density

00:08:16.930 --> 00:08:19.210
that has that weighted
in there, like so.

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:21.810
So this will, in fact, be--

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:25.540
so this entire integral, both
of these entire integrals,

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:27.340
are Lorentz scalars.

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:30.380
This is a proper
element of volume,

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:38.350
and so this is a proper Lorentz
covariant well-defined Lagrange

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:40.650
density.

00:08:40.650 --> 00:08:42.510
So whenever you have
an action principle,

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:50.180
you proceed via an
extremization procedure.

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:51.740
So suppose your Lagrangian--

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:53.532
I'm going to write this
very schematically.

00:08:53.532 --> 00:08:57.130
Suppose it depends on
some set of fields.

00:08:57.130 --> 00:09:14.310
When you extremize this, that
amounts to our requirement

00:09:14.310 --> 00:09:18.990
that the action be
stationary with respect

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:20.450
to a variation of the fields.

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:44.055
So if I vary my fields, I'm
going to vary my action.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.010
And let's just schematically
write this using

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:52.650
the first form of things here.

00:09:52.650 --> 00:09:57.600
I will then say, however,
my Lagrangian varies,

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:07.970
as I vary whatever fields it
depends on, this must be zero.

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:10.340
That is my stationarity
requirement.

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:13.880
For this to occur, for this to
be valid for arbitrary field

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:24.648
variations, I will
then deduce from this

00:10:24.648 --> 00:10:26.690
that the variation of the
Lagrange density itself

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:29.440
with those fields
must be equal to zero.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:32.270
When I do this, this will
then lead to Euler Lagrange

00:10:32.270 --> 00:10:33.710
equations for my fields.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:51.240
Now, many students in the
class may have already

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:53.110
seen things like this.

00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:56.610
But for those who have not, let
me work through a fairly simple

00:10:56.610 --> 00:10:58.060
example.

00:10:58.060 --> 00:11:01.260
So let's imagine that I have
a Lagrangian that just depends

00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:05.110
on a scalar field phi and
derivatives of that scalar

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:05.610
field.

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:17.710
So L is going to
depend on some phi

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:21.460
and derivatives of that phi.

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:24.130
In my notes actually, imagine
there might be multiple scalar

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:24.450
fields.

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:25.742
Let's just keep it simple here.

00:11:25.742 --> 00:11:29.650
We'll just have one scalar
field and its derivatives.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:31.270
When we do our
variation, it's going

00:11:31.270 --> 00:11:34.090
to be important that we treat
variations of the derivative

00:11:34.090 --> 00:11:37.630
differently from
variations of the field.

00:11:37.630 --> 00:11:41.118
At the moment, I'm going
to focus on flat spacetime.

00:11:41.118 --> 00:11:43.660
We'll see what happens when the
spacetime's a little bit more

00:11:43.660 --> 00:11:45.077
interesting in
just a few moments.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:54.740
And what I'm going
to do is imagine

00:11:54.740 --> 00:12:13.237
that phi varies like so, and its
derivative varies like so, OK?

00:12:13.237 --> 00:12:14.070
So let's apply this.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:16.590
I want to look at a variation
of this thing with respect

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:18.450
to my fields.

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:25.990
So when I do my variation
of the action S,

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:34.150
I get one term that will arise
in the variation in the field

00:12:34.150 --> 00:12:49.500
phi, and I will get
another term that

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.500
arises due to the variation
in the derivative.

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:56.340
That term is potentially a
little bit problematic for us.

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:58.260
I'm going to gloss over
a couple of details.

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:02.040
But essentially what you
want to do is, at this point,

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:04.470
apply integration by parts.

00:13:04.470 --> 00:13:06.030
When you apply
integration by parts,

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:09.350
you can move this derivative
onto this term here.

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:52.320
And in so doing, your delta S
becomes something like this.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:54.360
Caution-- I'm being a
little bit glib here.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:57.260
That is only true if--

00:13:57.260 --> 00:14:01.020
when you do this properly,
there is kind of a boundary term

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:03.217
that I'm assuming
can be discarded.

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:08.740
I don't want to get lost
in the weeds associated

00:14:08.740 --> 00:14:09.615
with that right here.

00:14:09.615 --> 00:14:12.168
Our goal is just to sort of
sketch the main physical ideas.

00:14:12.168 --> 00:14:13.710
But I will say that
this is something

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:15.670
that should be treated
with a little bit of care.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:17.170
And I highlight
this because there's

00:14:17.170 --> 00:14:21.070
going to be a similar step that
I'm going to sort of go over

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:24.120
with a little less care than I
would like as we move forward,

00:14:24.120 --> 00:14:26.970
and I'll comment on
that at that time.

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:29.280
Having done this and
assuming that the discarding

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:32.040
of the boundary term
is safe for me here--

00:14:34.872 --> 00:14:36.830
actually, let me just
make one further comment.

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:40.077
This is being done at
over all of spacetime.

00:14:40.077 --> 00:14:41.660
And so when I do
that, I'm essentially

00:14:41.660 --> 00:14:44.370
assuming that the boundary
is the boundary of infinity,

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:45.860
which doesn't really exist, OK?

00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:48.260
So that's one reason why you
can generally get rid of it

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:48.810
in this case.

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:50.810
And it turns out
to be fairly safe.

00:14:50.810 --> 00:14:52.663
I'm highlighting
this point because it

00:14:52.663 --> 00:14:54.080
should be stated
a little bit more

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:56.990
carefully than I
have it in my notes.

00:14:56.990 --> 00:14:59.293
And when we apply
this to gravity,

00:14:59.293 --> 00:15:00.710
there's a little
bit of a subtlety

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:05.637
there that I will
comment on at that time.

00:15:05.637 --> 00:15:07.220
For now, I'm just
going to say, great.

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:08.960
So that sort of works good.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:10.860
That works out very
good, very well.

00:15:10.860 --> 00:15:16.170
And in order for this
to be equal to zero,

00:15:16.170 --> 00:15:22.820
the term inside my square
braces must vanish,

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:38.410
and so I wind up with Euler
Lagrange equations, which

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:44.480
my field, my field phi, must
satisfy given the Lagrangian L,

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:45.700
OK?

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:47.380
Now let's just take
it one step further.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:50.890
So I haven't said yet where
the Lagrangian comes from, OK?

00:15:50.890 --> 00:15:54.070
As I sort of indicated, when
I sketch this over here,

00:15:54.070 --> 00:15:56.530
it's going to depend on the
nature of the field you study.

00:15:56.530 --> 00:16:01.150
So it's very common when you're
studying, say, a scalar field

00:16:01.150 --> 00:16:04.210
and flat spacetime
that you imagine

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:11.320
that your Lagrangian has what
we call a kinetic term, which

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:13.690
is proportional to
something that's quadratic--

00:16:17.626 --> 00:16:22.910
whoops-- in the
derivatives of your field.

00:16:22.910 --> 00:16:27.710
If it is massive, you
may have another term

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:32.127
which sort of looks almost like
a potential energy in which you

00:16:32.127 --> 00:16:34.460
get something that looks like
the field squared coupling

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:36.920
to a parameter with
the dimensions of mass.

00:16:43.850 --> 00:17:12.230
Take these derivatives,
so taking the derivative

00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:15.390
of this Lagrangian with
respect to the field,

00:17:15.390 --> 00:17:16.260
that's quite simple.

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:23.260
You just get m squared phi.

00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:31.830
Take the derivative with respect
to the field's derivative,

00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:33.600
what pops out of this is--

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:34.578
pardon me.

