00:40:09.630 --> 00:40:10.805
coefficients.

00:40:23.430 --> 00:40:28.140
When you do this, if you do
the calculation correctly,

00:40:28.140 --> 00:40:31.470
you, in fact, get both
the Einstein equation,

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:34.010
the Einstein-- so again,
we've not introduced a source.

00:40:34.010 --> 00:40:37.550
I'm going to talk about
source in just a moment.

00:40:37.550 --> 00:40:39.760
So the Einstein
equation with no source

00:40:39.760 --> 00:40:53.410
emerges, and you find
that your connection

00:40:53.410 --> 00:40:56.140
must be metric compatible.

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:06.100
In other words, the
connection is such

00:41:06.100 --> 00:41:10.960
that you are required to
have covariant derivative

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:13.027
of the metric equal to zero.

00:41:13.027 --> 00:41:14.860
It's actually a beautiful
little calculation

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:19.660
because we sort of argue that
this was going to be the case--

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:21.580
when we were talking
about how to define

00:41:21.580 --> 00:41:23.372
a covariant derivative,
we noted that there

00:41:23.372 --> 00:41:25.930
are many ways to define
a transport operation.

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:27.790
This ended up being
one that allowed us

00:41:27.790 --> 00:41:29.480
to define parallel transport.

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:31.750
That became something
that the physics drove us

00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:36.520
to selecting as a very natural
choice for our connection.

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:38.080
This variation
doesn't necessarily

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:39.850
know anything about
that, but it shows

00:41:39.850 --> 00:41:42.190
that when you do your
variational principle, treating

00:41:42.190 --> 00:41:45.430
metric and connection as
separate degrees of freedom,

00:41:45.430 --> 00:41:49.840
that parallel transport-driven
choice of the connection which

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:54.350
gives us the Christoffel symbols
emerges as the outcome of that.

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:59.205
Now, this is not a terribly
difficult calculation to do,

00:41:59.205 --> 00:42:01.330
but there's a lot of details
you have to get right.

00:42:01.330 --> 00:42:05.740
And I've got about a fourth
of it written up at this point

00:42:05.740 --> 00:42:08.590
and just haven't had a chance to
get all the details completely

00:42:08.590 --> 00:42:09.940
straightened out.

00:42:09.940 --> 00:42:11.847
I really hope to
have the bandwidth

00:42:11.847 --> 00:42:13.930
to finish it by the end
of the term, in which case

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:18.550
I will add it as supplemental
notes to the course.

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:21.910
The other thing you can do--

00:42:21.910 --> 00:42:25.360
so there's absolutely nothing
wrong with the approach

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:28.480
that we started doing in
which we vary the metric.

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:30.760
And we just assume
from the outset

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:33.490
that my connection
arises from the metric

00:42:33.490 --> 00:42:37.360
so that, the way we do it,
the connection and the metric

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:39.010
are not separate
degrees of freedom,

00:42:39.010 --> 00:42:42.010
but the connection
arises from the metric.

00:42:42.010 --> 00:42:43.430
And that is fine.

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:46.173
But if we do that, then when
you get down to this point,

00:42:46.173 --> 00:42:48.090
you just have to be a
little bit more careful.

00:42:48.090 --> 00:42:51.340
You essentially take this
argument that Carroll makes

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:57.400
and you have to just do
it with a lot more care.

00:42:57.400 --> 00:43:03.070
So what you need to do
is define the boundary

00:43:03.070 --> 00:43:07.822
associated with the divergence
integral very carefully--

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:13.060
whoops.

00:43:13.060 --> 00:43:14.560
Associated with
divergence integral.

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:48.200
In doing so, you have
to very carefully treat

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:50.045
the curvature on that boundary.

00:43:52.610 --> 00:43:55.337
So we are working
in four dimensions.

00:43:58.470 --> 00:44:09.088
So it's a three dimensional
boundary of our 4D spacetime.

00:44:13.148 --> 00:44:14.690
You can sort of
think of the boundary

00:44:14.690 --> 00:44:16.400
as being a particular
sort of slice

00:44:16.400 --> 00:44:18.563
through four
dimensional space time.

00:44:18.563 --> 00:44:20.480
You pick a particular
three dimensional slice,

00:44:20.480 --> 00:44:23.335
redefine that as the boundary
region of this integral.

00:44:23.335 --> 00:44:24.710
And that requires
us to introduce

00:44:24.710 --> 00:44:27.130
some additional concepts.

00:44:27.130 --> 00:44:30.680
In particular, once you
pick out a particular slice

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:34.250
of space time, some of
the curvature associated

00:44:34.250 --> 00:44:36.920
with the metric on
that slice isn't

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:39.560
intrinsic to the
spacetime itself,

00:44:39.560 --> 00:44:42.530
but it's imposed
on the space time

00:44:42.530 --> 00:44:45.410
by the manner in which
you have made that slice.

00:44:45.410 --> 00:44:48.320
Sort of in the same way
that if I have a cylinder,

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:50.510
the surface of a cylinder
is intrinsically flat.

00:44:50.510 --> 00:44:53.030
If I put two geodesics on it
and I parallel transport them

00:44:53.030 --> 00:44:56.870
around, they remain perfectly
parallel forever and forever

00:44:56.870 --> 00:44:57.680
and forever.

00:44:57.680 --> 00:44:59.840
But it sure as
hell looks curved.

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:03.150
But that is because I have
taken this flat surface

00:45:03.150 --> 00:45:04.670
and I have folded it up.

00:45:04.670 --> 00:45:07.460
I have embedded it in a higher
dimensional space in such a way

00:45:07.460 --> 00:45:10.880
that there's extrinsic curvature
that's been imposed on it.

00:45:10.880 --> 00:45:14.150
When you are carefully looking
at the boundary of a four

00:45:14.150 --> 00:45:16.910
dimensional spacetime, you also
need to very carefully treat

00:45:16.910 --> 00:45:19.220
the extrinsic curvature
associated with how you put

00:45:19.220 --> 00:45:21.290
that boundary on top of things.

00:45:21.290 --> 00:45:26.388
When you do this
correctly, you find

00:45:26.388 --> 00:45:28.430
you need to be a little
bit more careful with how

00:45:28.430 --> 00:45:29.990
you define the Lagrangian.

00:45:47.662 --> 00:45:49.870
And when you, in fact, do
that, it actually turns out

00:45:49.870 --> 00:45:53.800
you don't get that
divergence term at all.

00:45:53.800 --> 00:46:03.470
You get sort of a counter term
that cancels this guy away.

00:46:03.470 --> 00:46:05.950
So for students who are
interested in seeing this

00:46:05.950 --> 00:46:08.350
explored and discussed
in a lot more rigor

00:46:08.350 --> 00:46:11.530
than I am prepared
to do, this is

00:46:11.530 --> 00:46:21.860
discussed in appendix E of
Robert Wald's textbook, General

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:23.342
Relativity.

00:46:29.670 --> 00:46:32.180
I will simply comment
that Wald's textbook

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:36.020
is one of the most mathematical
textbooks on this topic.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:39.650
He does everything with great
rigor and a lot of care.

00:46:39.650 --> 00:46:43.370
And the appendices is where
he puts his particularly

00:46:43.370 --> 00:46:45.120
high-level, grotty details.

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:47.150
So this really is
something that is

00:46:47.150 --> 00:46:49.670
beyond the level of where
we do a one semester

00:46:49.670 --> 00:46:52.370
course like 8.962.

00:46:52.370 --> 00:46:54.740
So it's unfortunate it
sort of pops up here,

00:46:54.740 --> 00:46:56.240
which is why a
textbook like Carroll

00:46:56.240 --> 00:46:58.790
does this in a
somewhat glib way.

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:02.318
I am personally a fan of
doing this Palatini variation.

00:47:02.318 --> 00:47:03.860
And so, as I've
emphasized, I'm going

00:47:03.860 --> 00:47:08.630
to try to clean that up
and make that available.

00:47:08.630 --> 00:47:15.690
So what all of this
ends up telling us--

00:47:20.490 --> 00:47:22.240
so let's take the
optimistic point of view

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:28.420
here that we have either
accepted the somewhat

00:47:28.420 --> 00:47:30.610
glib argument that we
can discard that term,

00:47:30.610 --> 00:47:34.510
or we sat down and we slog
through appendix E of Wald,

00:47:34.510 --> 00:47:37.840
or we wrote up the
Palatini variation.

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:40.540
Doing this variation in
that case then leads us

00:47:40.540 --> 00:48:04.780
to G alpha beta equals zero.

00:48:04.780 --> 00:48:07.810
This is the Einstein
equation when

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:10.950
there is no source, when the
stress energy tensor is zero.

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:15.640
This is often called the
vacuum Einstein equation.

00:48:25.740 --> 00:48:28.500
More generally, we
should treat the action

00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:33.090
that we are varying as the
Einstein-Hilbert action

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:35.100
plus an action
associated with matter.

00:48:35.100 --> 00:48:43.550
So a more general
form would be to write

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:55.510
S as the integral d4x square
root minus G R over 16 pi

00:48:55.510 --> 00:48:58.870
G plus the Lagrangian for--

00:48:58.870 --> 00:49:00.760
I'm just going to
say m for matter.

00:49:00.760 --> 00:49:02.050
Could be matter and fields.

00:49:05.920 --> 00:49:18.680
If you do that, then when
you look at your variation

00:49:18.680 --> 00:49:23.210
and enforce that the variation
of the action equals zero,

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:25.640
this leads you to an
equation of the form--

00:49:50.620 --> 00:49:53.150
that's given by this.

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:59.380
And so up to a numerical
factor, which I'll write out

00:49:59.380 --> 00:50:01.060
in just a second,
you can basically

00:50:01.060 --> 00:50:04.210
see that this variation
of my matter Lagrangian

00:50:04.210 --> 00:50:06.580
becomes the stress
energy tensor.

00:50:16.345 --> 00:50:17.970
In particular, if
you just look at this

00:50:17.970 --> 00:50:33.940
and say, oh, I am going to
define T alpha beta as minus 2

00:50:33.940 --> 00:50:46.840
divided by square root
of minus G, like this,

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:48.670
then the Einstein-Hilbert
variation

00:50:48.670 --> 00:50:54.640
gives me exactly the
same Einstein equation

00:50:54.640 --> 00:50:57.690
as we had before.

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:00.270
I have a set of exercises
in the notes, which

00:51:00.270 --> 00:51:03.990
I'm not going to go
through because they're

00:51:03.990 --> 00:51:05.347
slightly tedious.

00:51:05.347 --> 00:51:07.680
And I think I'm going to
actually end a little bit early

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:08.670
here.

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:11.880
But I want to just describe
one of the ways in which this

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:13.200
can be used.

00:51:13.200 --> 00:51:28.060
So suppose I pick as
my matter Lagrangian

00:51:28.060 --> 00:51:34.180
minus one fourth
f mu nu, f mu nu,

00:51:34.180 --> 00:51:38.440
where f mu nu is the Faraday
tensor that describes

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:39.760
electric and magnetic fields.

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:04.050
So what I want to
do is show that,

00:52:04.050 --> 00:52:06.590
by applying this variational
principle that I've

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:08.730
defined over there to this--

00:52:08.730 --> 00:52:11.460
but this gives me exactly
the stress energy tensor

00:52:11.460 --> 00:52:15.120
that one expects for
electromagnetic fields.

00:52:27.320 --> 00:52:33.250
OK, so defining my
electromagnetic action,

00:52:33.250 --> 00:52:37.440
pull out the overall
factor of minus one fourth,

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:41.960
I integrate over my
spacetime coordinates.

00:52:45.250 --> 00:52:49.270
And then notice the
way this is set up.

00:52:49.270 --> 00:52:54.320
So I have f mu nu upstairs,
f mu nu downstairs.

00:52:54.320 --> 00:53:04.210
Let's write my f mu nu upstairs
as f alpha beta downstairs

00:53:04.210 --> 00:53:05.980
but with enough
prefactors of the metric

00:53:05.980 --> 00:53:08.390
to raise those indices.

00:53:08.390 --> 00:53:10.100
So I do a variation on this.

00:53:16.660 --> 00:53:19.650
And the way I'm going to do
it is I will vary the metric.

00:53:23.080 --> 00:53:40.140
When I do this, I will
not vary the fields, OK?

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:43.890
If one does variations of
those things, you can do that,

00:53:43.890 --> 00:53:46.470
and you can use that to do
things like define your field

00:53:46.470 --> 00:53:47.340
equations.

00:53:47.340 --> 00:53:49.800
But what I want to do is
just see how, by varying

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:52.830
how the metric couples
do these things,

00:53:52.830 --> 00:53:55.250
the stress energy
tensor emerges.

00:53:55.250 --> 00:53:58.640
So in my notes, I go
through this calculation

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:00.930
with some care.

00:54:00.930 --> 00:54:42.360
And what emerges at the end is
something that looks like this.

00:54:46.330 --> 00:54:48.340
And in fact, it's
not too hard to show.

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:50.800
Dig into something, a
textbook like Jackson,

00:54:50.800 --> 00:54:53.050
what is in square braces
there is, in fact,

00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:56.920
the standard stress
energy tensor associated

00:54:56.920 --> 00:54:59.030
with the electromagnetic field.

00:54:59.030 --> 00:55:01.780
So this technique, this
definition I've put in here,

00:55:01.780 --> 00:55:07.130
it does work in all the
cases that we know about.

00:55:07.130 --> 00:55:10.180
And so this
variational principal

00:55:10.180 --> 00:55:11.973
root to the field equations--

00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:21.180
so punchline is
selecting L equals

00:55:21.180 --> 00:55:34.920
R yields the Einstein
field equations

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:36.450
upon variation of the metric.

00:55:44.100 --> 00:55:47.638
So I'll take a
sip of water here.

00:55:47.638 --> 00:55:49.680
And then the question I
want you to sort of think

00:55:49.680 --> 00:55:52.200
of at this point is, so what?

00:55:57.410 --> 00:56:02.300
I mean, it's nice that there
is a second way to do this.

00:56:02.300 --> 00:56:05.382
But did we need it?

00:56:05.382 --> 00:56:06.840
Is it really
important that we have

00:56:06.840 --> 00:56:09.390
the second way of doing this?

00:56:09.390 --> 00:56:11.870
Well, here I want to
come back to a comment I

00:56:11.870 --> 00:56:17.150
made as I began this lecture,
which was that our guiding

00:56:17.150 --> 00:56:23.360
principle for formulating
this Lagrangian

00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:29.330
was that it has to be built
out of curvature tensors,

00:56:29.330 --> 00:56:30.965
and it has to be a scalar.

00:56:35.730 --> 00:56:39.690
I would argue that
the Ricci scalar

00:56:39.690 --> 00:56:43.130
is the simplest such
construction that does that.

00:57:06.380 --> 00:57:10.880
But it is not the only scalar
made from curvature tensors

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:11.630
that will do this.

00:57:25.640 --> 00:57:30.790
Imagine you wanted
to modify gravity,

00:57:30.790 --> 00:57:33.290
or you wanted to come
up with a framework that

00:57:33.290 --> 00:57:35.660
was consistent with
general relativity.

00:57:35.660 --> 00:57:40.340
And remember, L equals R
gives me general relativity,

00:57:40.340 --> 00:57:43.720
gives me Einstein's
field equations.

00:57:43.720 --> 00:57:47.210
It gives me Einstein's
theory of gravity.

00:57:47.210 --> 00:57:51.110
Suppose I want to
modify it in a way

00:57:51.110 --> 00:57:54.590
such that things look just
like Einstein's gravity

00:57:54.590 --> 00:58:00.440
for most of the universe,
but perhaps small differences

00:58:00.440 --> 00:58:04.070
kick in when the curvature
is small in some sense that

00:58:04.070 --> 00:58:05.674
will need to be characterized.

00:58:42.270 --> 00:58:45.690
Well, one way you could
imagine doing this

00:58:45.690 --> 00:58:48.410
is by adding a correction.

00:58:48.410 --> 00:59:04.700
Suppose we try L hat equals R
minus alpha over R. That sort

00:59:04.700 --> 00:59:07.610
of suggests that
this is going to lead

00:59:07.610 --> 00:59:21.360
to corrections to the
framework of gravity

00:59:21.360 --> 00:59:30.910
when the curvature scale is less
than or of order square root

00:59:30.910 --> 00:59:31.410
of alpha.

00:59:39.760 --> 00:59:43.610
It's actually a work of a
couple pages of algebra.

00:59:43.610 --> 00:59:46.060
I can take this
modified Lagrangian.

00:59:46.060 --> 00:59:49.240
I can go through exactly
this variational principles

00:59:49.240 --> 00:59:50.470
that we spent today doing.

00:59:53.860 --> 01:00:01.390
And when I do so, I find a
new field equation coupling

01:00:01.390 --> 01:00:05.425
spacetime to my sources.

01:00:13.120 --> 01:00:19.450
So vary the metric,
enforce stationarity

01:00:19.450 --> 01:00:33.550
of the action, what you get
is a field equation that

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:34.300
looks like this.

01:01:17.300 --> 01:01:21.380
Notice, set that
coupling alpha to zero

01:01:21.380 --> 01:01:27.410
and it says G alpha beta equals
8 pi newtons GT alpha beta.

01:01:27.410 --> 01:01:30.560
But introduce this
little scale here,

01:01:30.560 --> 01:01:32.990
suddenly you've got all
this other stuff emerging.

01:01:36.220 --> 01:01:38.640
This is an idea that was
proposed and explored

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:41.550
in a paper, if you want to
read a bit more about this,

01:01:41.550 --> 01:01:46.230
by Sean Carroll et al,
published in Physical Review

01:01:46.230 --> 01:01:49.770
D. It's now almost coming
up on its second decade.

01:02:03.260 --> 01:02:08.360
So the reason why Sean and his
collaborators developed this,

01:02:08.360 --> 01:02:10.670
I mentioned in my
previous lecture

01:02:10.670 --> 01:02:15.110
that there's observations that
have driven us to consider

01:02:15.110 --> 01:02:18.260
whether there is, in fact,
a cosmological constant

01:02:18.260 --> 01:02:22.610
contributing to the large scale
structure of our universe.

01:02:22.610 --> 01:02:26.300
And like good
scientists, you're always

01:02:26.300 --> 01:02:29.060
looking for alternate
hypotheses that

01:02:29.060 --> 01:02:32.060
could be tested or falsified.

01:02:32.060 --> 01:02:33.740
And so what Carroll
et al pointed out

01:02:33.740 --> 01:02:41.840
was the universe's accelerated
expansion, so the behavior that

01:02:41.840 --> 01:02:45.080
is driving us to consider the
possibility the cosmological

01:02:45.080 --> 01:02:48.230
constant, it's coming on
very, very large scales

01:02:48.230 --> 01:02:50.570
where the curvature
is quite small.

01:02:50.570 --> 01:02:54.470
Laboratory and solar system and
many other astrophysical tests

01:02:54.470 --> 01:02:56.330
of the foundations
of general relativity

01:02:56.330 --> 01:02:57.800
aren't as strong there.

01:02:57.800 --> 01:03:00.740
So why not try something a
little bit out of the box?

01:03:00.740 --> 01:03:04.250
And they said, let's think
about a theory of gravity

01:03:04.250 --> 01:03:07.160
in which there are potentially
important modifications when

01:03:07.160 --> 01:03:09.770
the curvature is small.

01:03:09.770 --> 01:03:10.940
This is what resulted.

01:03:10.940 --> 01:03:14.390
And they showed, actually,
that by appropriately choosing

01:03:14.390 --> 01:03:16.690
the parameter alpha,
actually, this

01:03:16.690 --> 01:03:18.440
is a point that's worth making.

01:03:18.440 --> 01:03:21.710
Notice this is
introducing a scale, OK?

01:03:21.710 --> 01:03:24.410
The theory doesn't
tell us what alpha is.

01:03:24.410 --> 01:03:27.380
From the standpoint of the
analysis that motivated it,

01:03:27.380 --> 01:03:29.630
it was a phenomenological
knob that they sort of

01:03:29.630 --> 01:03:32.510
tweaked to see whether they
could explain observations.

01:03:32.510 --> 01:03:34.040
And indeed, they
did find that they

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:37.790
could get pretty good
explanation of the accelerating

01:03:37.790 --> 01:03:40.670
expansion of the universe
with this modified

01:03:40.670 --> 01:03:42.230
theory of gravity.

01:03:42.230 --> 01:03:46.070
But all good theories
are testable.

01:03:46.070 --> 01:03:47.780
They're falsifiable.

01:03:47.780 --> 01:03:49.430
They give rise to
hypotheses that you

01:03:49.430 --> 01:03:51.050
can compare against data.

01:03:51.050 --> 01:03:55.670
It turns out, if you
tune alpha to make

01:03:55.670 --> 01:03:57.890
the expansion of
the universe work,

01:03:57.890 --> 01:04:00.290
you get the orbits of the
planets in our solar system

01:04:00.290 --> 01:04:01.670
wrong.

01:04:01.670 --> 01:04:04.400
So this ended up not
being a viable theory,

01:04:04.400 --> 01:04:07.980
but it was a pretty cool
thing to explore, OK?

01:04:07.980 --> 01:04:11.150
And I think it serves as
a really wonderful example

01:04:11.150 --> 01:04:16.460
of how, in a theory of gravity,
one formulates a hypothesis

01:04:16.460 --> 01:04:17.690
and then tests it.

01:04:17.690 --> 01:04:20.390
And then giving Sean
and his colleagues

01:04:20.390 --> 01:04:22.243
all their due,
cheerfully accepting

01:04:22.243 --> 01:04:24.410
the falsification when it
turned out it didn't work.

01:04:26.832 --> 01:04:28.790
You know, it's a very,
very nice piece of work.

01:04:28.790 --> 01:04:30.590
And I think it just
is a really good idea

01:04:30.590 --> 01:04:34.160
of the power of this
action-based method

01:04:34.160 --> 01:04:38.180
for considering modifications
to your theory of gravity, OK?

01:04:38.180 --> 01:04:39.680
And it really
highlights the fact

01:04:39.680 --> 01:04:42.830
that just choosing
your Lagrange density

01:04:42.830 --> 01:04:46.340
as the Ricci scalar, that's
the simplest possible thing it

01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:46.840
can make.

01:04:46.840 --> 01:04:48.980
And that is a sense in
which general relativity

01:04:48.980 --> 01:04:52.820
is the simplest of all
possible relativistic theories

01:04:52.820 --> 01:04:53.870
of gravity.

01:04:53.870 --> 01:04:55.658
Let me just give you
another example of--

01:04:55.658 --> 01:04:56.825
actually, two more examples.

01:05:00.648 --> 01:05:02.690
I'm not going to go through
them in great detail,

01:05:02.690 --> 01:05:04.760
but just sketching the
way people sometimes

01:05:04.760 --> 01:05:09.160
imagine modifying gravity.

01:05:09.160 --> 01:05:21.800
So suppose I choose as
my gravitational action

01:05:21.800 --> 01:05:29.340
my normal Einstein-Hilbert
term plus a term

01:05:29.340 --> 01:05:33.570
that goes as the Ricci
curvature squared.

01:05:33.570 --> 01:05:37.950
This is something that you
might expect to become important

01:05:37.950 --> 01:05:39.540
when the curvature is large.

01:06:06.528 --> 01:06:09.640
OK, so when R is
greater than R of order,

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:13.390
1 over beta, the second term,
will become more important

01:06:13.390 --> 01:06:14.380
than the first term.

01:06:14.380 --> 01:06:16.780
Again, we've introduced a scale.

01:06:16.780 --> 01:06:20.400
There is some
theoretical prejudice

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:26.690
among the community that thinks
about these kinds of models

01:06:26.690 --> 01:06:28.760
that perhaps this
scale has something

01:06:28.760 --> 01:06:32.690
to do with where quantum
gravity effects begin to kick in

01:06:32.690 --> 01:06:35.725
and classical general
relativity must be modified.

01:06:35.725 --> 01:06:37.100
And so you can
imagine, you might

01:06:37.100 --> 01:06:40.460
think that this beta
is on the order of,

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:44.261
when you work in units where
G and C are equal to 1,

01:06:44.261 --> 01:06:45.900
H bar to the minus 1.

01:06:50.670 --> 01:06:54.140
Actions like this often
emerge when you are studying--

01:06:54.140 --> 01:06:56.580
they often show up when
you are studying theories

01:06:56.580 --> 01:06:59.850
in which general relativity is
itself an effective theory that

01:06:59.850 --> 01:07:04.392
comes about from averaging over
small scale degrees of freedom.

01:07:04.392 --> 01:07:05.100
One more example.

01:07:19.310 --> 01:07:25.660
What if there were, in
addition to the tensor,

01:07:25.660 --> 01:07:28.670
the metric tensor
which describes

01:07:28.670 --> 01:07:30.980
the geometry of space time--

01:07:30.980 --> 01:07:39.720
what if the manner in which
the metric tensor coupled

01:07:39.720 --> 01:07:45.200
to its source varied depending
on some additional field that

01:07:45.200 --> 01:07:46.808
filled all of spacetime?

01:08:21.170 --> 01:08:34.260
So you can imagine that your
gravitational action took

01:08:34.260 --> 01:08:42.689
the usual form,
but it was modified

01:08:42.689 --> 01:08:49.200
by some kind of a scalar
field that might itself depend

01:08:49.200 --> 01:08:52.096
upon spacetime curvature, OK?

01:08:52.096 --> 01:08:56.640
And you can imagine
then supplementing this

01:08:56.640 --> 01:09:00.000
with an action for
the scalar field,

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:02.399
which, up to an overall constant
at least, I will write--

01:09:19.189 --> 01:09:23.819
theories of this sort are
called scalar tensor series.

01:09:23.819 --> 01:09:26.760
And what they
essentially amount to is

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:28.597
you imagine that
there is some field

01:09:28.597 --> 01:09:30.180
in addition to the
metric of spacetime

01:09:30.180 --> 01:09:31.310
which is affecting gravity.

01:09:31.310 --> 01:09:33.102
You can almost think
of them as essentially

01:09:33.102 --> 01:09:38.850
saying that the effective
gravitational constant varies

01:09:38.850 --> 01:09:41.729
depending upon the strength of
the gravitational interaction.

01:09:41.729 --> 01:09:47.609
So perhaps down
near a black hole

01:09:47.609 --> 01:09:52.590
the Newton constant is bigger
or smaller or something than way

01:09:52.590 --> 01:09:53.700
out in empty space.

01:09:59.950 --> 01:10:03.310
Theories of this kind arise--

01:10:03.310 --> 01:10:06.580
I should say terms of
this kind and the action--

01:10:06.580 --> 01:10:15.400
quite naturally in a lot of
work in theoretical attempts

01:10:15.400 --> 01:10:18.525
to quantize gravity,
things like that.

01:10:18.525 --> 01:10:20.650
And so people like to pay
attention to these things

01:10:20.650 --> 01:10:23.770
and to see what kind of generic
predictions they can make.

01:10:23.770 --> 01:10:27.340
These are known as
scalar tensor theories.

01:10:32.290 --> 01:10:34.600
And if you're interested
in seeing more about them,

01:10:34.600 --> 01:10:40.772
Sean Carroll's textbook has a
full section describing them.

01:10:40.772 --> 01:10:41.980
A little bit out of date now.

01:10:48.070 --> 01:10:51.860
One thing that's kind of
interesting as we sort of think

01:10:51.860 --> 01:10:53.860
about how the subject has
evolved over the years

01:10:53.860 --> 01:10:55.960
that I've been teaching
it is that when

01:10:55.960 --> 01:10:59.720
you have both a tensor
component, in other words,

01:10:59.720 --> 01:11:02.260
a spacetime metric coupling
to your stress energy

01:11:02.260 --> 01:11:05.290
tensor and you have
a scalar field,

01:11:05.290 --> 01:11:07.540
you change the
dynamics of the theory.

01:11:07.540 --> 01:11:10.870
And that ends up doing
things like changing

01:11:10.870 --> 01:11:12.670
the character of
gravitational radiation

01:11:12.670 --> 01:11:14.260
that is emitted from a system.

01:11:14.260 --> 01:11:17.860
And so, very recently,
the most stringent limits

01:11:17.860 --> 01:11:21.430
on these possible modifications
to general relativity

01:11:21.430 --> 01:11:24.520
have come about from things
like LIGO observations

01:11:24.520 --> 01:11:27.520
which have looked at
coalescences of black holes

01:11:27.520 --> 01:11:29.110
and neutron stars.

01:11:29.110 --> 01:11:32.080
And all of their
measurements are

01:11:32.080 --> 01:11:34.840
consistent with
there being no scalar

01:11:34.840 --> 01:11:36.268
modification to these things.

01:11:36.268 --> 01:11:37.810
And so it helps to
set limits on many

01:11:37.810 --> 01:11:42.100
of these theoretical frameworks
that introduce and look

01:11:42.100 --> 01:11:46.750
at modifications to
GR which are motivated

01:11:46.750 --> 01:11:51.070
by certain considerations.

01:11:51.070 --> 01:11:54.910
This concludes the
first half of 8.962.

01:11:54.910 --> 01:11:59.620
So if I'm just going to do a
quick recap of where we are

01:11:59.620 --> 01:12:04.060
and where we are going, where
I want you to sort of sit

01:12:04.060 --> 01:12:10.660
with things right now is that
you have this arsenal which

01:12:10.660 --> 01:12:15.130
basically tells you that,
given the metric of spacetime,

01:12:15.130 --> 01:12:16.840
you can compute the
motion of bodies--

01:12:21.680 --> 01:12:28.090
this is done using
by geodesics--

01:12:28.090 --> 01:12:33.250
you can characterize
the curvature

01:12:33.250 --> 01:12:41.900
of that spacetime which
tells you about tidal fields,

01:12:41.900 --> 01:12:46.640
and you now, as of
these last two lectures,

01:12:46.640 --> 01:12:54.630
know how to get this by solving
the Einstein field equation.

01:12:58.390 --> 01:13:00.640
What we will do in
the remaining lectures

01:13:00.640 --> 01:13:02.290
that I'll be recording
and distributing

01:13:02.290 --> 01:13:09.060
through this course's website
is solving this equation

01:13:09.060 --> 01:13:11.550
and exploring the properties
of these solutions.

01:13:11.550 --> 01:13:16.423
And so let me just sort
of say this equation,

01:13:16.423 --> 01:13:17.840
if you go back to
think about what

01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:20.270
goes into this-- at the
beginning of my next lecture

01:13:20.270 --> 01:13:21.860
which I'll be
recording tomorrow,

01:13:21.860 --> 01:13:23.570
we'll go through
this in some care.

01:13:23.570 --> 01:13:27.230
But if you just think of this
as a partial differential

01:13:27.230 --> 01:13:32.730
equation for the metric,
it is a god-awful mess, OK?

01:13:32.730 --> 01:13:34.650
There's no nice way to put it.

01:13:34.650 --> 01:13:36.440
I mean, it's just
a horrible mess

01:13:36.440 --> 01:13:40.840
of coupled, non-linear,
partial differential equations.

01:13:40.840 --> 01:13:44.330
We are going to look at
three ways of solving this.

01:13:55.050 --> 01:14:01.682
Method one, we will think about
a kind of weak field expansion.

01:14:07.950 --> 01:14:12.330
I'm going to imagine that
the spacetime corresponding

01:14:12.330 --> 01:14:21.670
to the sources we are studying
looks like flat spacetime

01:14:21.670 --> 01:14:24.190
plus a small correction.

01:14:24.190 --> 01:14:27.520
That will allow me to take
this horrible coupled,

01:14:27.520 --> 01:14:30.840
non-linear mess
and linearize, OK?

01:14:30.840 --> 01:14:33.910
We will lay out the principles
for doing that methodically

01:14:33.910 --> 01:14:37.400
in the beginning of
the next lecture.

01:14:37.400 --> 01:14:47.710
Method two, we'll
see what happens

01:14:47.710 --> 01:14:48.895
when we assert a symmetry.

01:14:52.730 --> 01:14:55.730
One of the reasons why those
equations are such a mess

01:14:55.730 --> 01:14:57.770
is that, in general,
there's just

01:14:57.770 --> 01:15:00.200
a tremendous number
of terms that

01:15:00.200 --> 01:15:04.640
are coupling to one another, all
sorts of things tying together,

01:15:04.640 --> 01:15:06.470
and it's just very,
very complicated.

01:15:06.470 --> 01:15:09.200
But if we imagine that
everything is, say, spherical

01:15:09.200 --> 01:15:11.600
symmetric, then
that dramatically

01:15:11.600 --> 01:15:13.580
reduces the number
of degrees of freedom

01:15:13.580 --> 01:15:17.750
that the spacetime could have
even as a matter of principle.

01:15:17.750 --> 01:15:21.020
And so we will actually
start by beginning

01:15:21.020 --> 01:15:24.680
to explore the most
symmetric space times of all.

01:15:24.680 --> 01:15:27.200
And I will lay out
exactly what that means.

01:15:27.200 --> 01:15:31.550
And that actually turns out,
at least to within our ability

01:15:31.550 --> 01:15:33.580
to observationally probe this--

01:15:33.580 --> 01:15:36.080
that appears to describe our
universe on the largest scales.

01:15:36.080 --> 01:15:38.450
And so when we do the largest,
the most symmetric things

01:15:38.450 --> 01:15:41.540
possible, that
gives us spacetimes

01:15:41.540 --> 01:15:45.800
that worked very well
for describing cosmology.

01:15:45.800 --> 01:15:48.560
Making things a little bit less
symmetric but still highly,

01:15:48.560 --> 01:15:52.370
highly symmetric, that allows
us to describe very strong field

01:15:52.370 --> 01:15:54.840
objects, things which
I'm going to call--

01:15:54.840 --> 01:15:56.750
I'm going to just
call them stars.

01:15:56.750 --> 01:15:58.670
What I really mean
by that are these

01:15:58.670 --> 01:16:01.550
are objects that are just
self gravitating circle fluid

01:16:01.550 --> 01:16:03.650
balls, OK?

01:16:03.650 --> 01:16:06.290
And we will see how they can
sort of hold themselves up

01:16:06.290 --> 01:16:08.878
against their own gravity, what
their spacetime looks like.

01:16:08.878 --> 01:16:10.670
There's all sorts of
interesting properties

01:16:10.670 --> 01:16:11.720
that emerge from them.

01:16:11.720 --> 01:16:14.090
And eventually we
actually find that you

01:16:14.090 --> 01:16:18.290
reach a set of configurations
where there is no--

01:16:18.290 --> 01:16:22.550
no fluid can be allowed by the--

01:16:22.550 --> 01:16:23.960
let me try that sentence again.

01:16:23.960 --> 01:16:27.890
You can find configurations
such that no fluid allowable

01:16:27.890 --> 01:16:32.330
by the laws of physics can
give you a stable object.

01:16:32.330 --> 01:16:35.060
They produce black holes.

01:16:35.060 --> 01:16:37.940
That will basically
take us, essentially,

01:16:37.940 --> 01:16:39.400
to the end of the course, OK?

01:16:39.400 --> 01:16:41.990
These two things have
a tremendous amount

01:16:41.990 --> 01:16:43.440
of content in them.

01:16:43.440 --> 01:16:47.660
And this is where a huge
amount of the literature

01:16:47.660 --> 01:16:50.120
on general relativity
has focused its attention

01:16:50.120 --> 01:16:52.960
over the past several decades.

01:16:52.960 --> 01:16:59.730
In my last lecture or so,
I'm going to briefly describe

01:16:59.730 --> 01:17:00.690
general solutions.

01:17:06.240 --> 01:17:09.720
What do you do if
there is no symmetry,

01:17:09.720 --> 01:17:13.290
there is no weak expansion,
no weak parameter

01:17:13.290 --> 01:17:14.760
you can expand in?

01:17:14.760 --> 01:17:19.320
You just have to deal with
the non-linear, bloody mess

01:17:19.320 --> 01:17:25.020
that these equations are
and then try to solve it.

01:17:25.020 --> 01:17:27.810
And what this will do is allow
me to explore and tell you

01:17:27.810 --> 01:17:32.700
a little bit about the field
of numerical relativity, which

01:17:32.700 --> 01:17:34.950
is what you do
when you just want

01:17:34.950 --> 01:17:38.580
to solve these things with no
approximations, no assumptions

01:17:38.580 --> 01:17:40.410
that simplify it whatsoever.

01:17:40.410 --> 01:17:43.740
Just take Einstein's
field equations,

01:17:43.740 --> 01:17:46.380
put it into a
computer, write a code,

01:17:46.380 --> 01:17:50.590
